_prev_prog_3.Description:
The off-site consequence analysis for the anhydrous ammonia system indicated that public and environmental receptors were located within the worst case release scenario impact zone, a radius of 4.9 miles from the storage tank.  Therefore, the plant has prepared their RMP prevention program to a Program 3 level.

Additionally, anhydrous ammonia is a listed chemical covered under the OSHA Process Safety Management (PSM) standard (codified in 29 CFR 1910.119).  Since anhydrous ammonia will be stored in amounts greater than the 10,000-pound threshold quantity, the facility is required to prepare a written PSM plan.  The required elements for PSM and RMP Program 3 prevention programs are identical, and are covered in this plan. 

PROCESS SAFETY INFORMATION [40 CFR 68.65] 
In accordance with the schedule set forth in 40 CFR 68.67, the Dogwood Energy Facility (Plant) completed a compilation of written process safety information before conducting the process hazard analysis required by the rule.  The compilation of written process safety information enabled the Plant management and employees involved in operating the process to identify and understand the hazards posed by the anhydrous ammonia storage and usage systems.  The process safety information includes information pertaining to the hazards of anhydrous ammonia, information pertaining to the technology of the process, and information pertaining to the equipment in the process.

This RMP contains a Material Safety Data Sheet for anhydrous ammonia that included the following information:

?    Toxicity data;
?    Permissible exposure limits;
?    Physical data;
?    Reactivity data:
?    Corrosivity data;
?    Thermal and chemical stability data; and
?    Hazardous effects of inadvertent mixing of different materials that could foreseeably occur.

The plant will update the MSDS sheet in this section as appropriate.

This RMP contains information pertaining to the technology of the anhydrous ammonia process including: 
?    Piping and instrument diagrams (P&ID's);
?    Equipment layout diagrams;
?    Process chemistry;
?    Maximum intended inventory;
?    Safe upper and lower limits for such items as temperatures, pressures, flows or compositions; 
?    Materials of construction
?    Electrical classification;
?    Relief system design and design basis;
?    Ventilation system design;
?    Design codes and standards employed;
?    Material and energy balances for processes built after June 21, 1999; and
?    Safety systems (e.g. interlocks, detection or suppression systems).

This information is contained within the Ammonia Supply and Storage Equipment Specification (Specification 64371.65.0221) and the Ammonia Storage and Handling System Operation and Maintenance (O&M) Manual dated 11/08/00, that are maintained in the Plant Engineers office.  Relevant sections of the O&M Manual have been provided in this section.

PROCESS HAZARD ANALYSIS [40 CFR 68.67]

The Plant has performed an initial process hazard analysis on the anhydrous ammonia process covered by this part using the Hazard and Operability Study (HAZOP) method.  The process hazard analysis identifies, evaluates, and rates the hazards involved in the process.  Factors included in the review included process hazards, number of potentially affected employees, age of the process, and operating history of similar processes.  The process hazard analysis was completed prior to plant start-up in 2001 and includes the OSHA PSM requirements of 29 CFR 1910.119(e).

The anhydrous ammonia process hazard analysis addresses the hazards of the process.  The HAZOP identifies potential incidents that may cause a loss of ammonia from the system which is included in the Process Hazard Analysis section of this RMP.  

The process hazard analysis was performed by a team with expertise in engineering and process operations.  The team included at least one plant employee who has experience and knowledge specific to the anhydrous ammonia process.  The team facilitator had knowledge of the HAZOP methodology.                                                                                                          
At least every five (5) years after the completion of the initial process hazard analysis, the process hazard analysis shall be updated and revalidated by a qualified team, to assure that the process hazard analysis is consistent with the current process.

OPERATING PROCEDURES [40 CFR 68.69] 

The Plant has implemented written operating procedures developed by Peerless Mfg. Co., the system supplier, which provides clear instructions for safely conducting activities regarding the anhydrous ammonia process.  These instructions are included in the O&M Manual, with relevant portions included in this section of the RMP.  

Plant management has reviewed the operating procedures to make sure they address the following required elements:

?    Steps for each operating phase including initial startup, normal operations, temporary operations, emergency shutdown including the conditions under which emergency shutdown is required;  
?    The assignment of shutdown responsibility to qualified operators to ensure that emergency shutdown is executed in a safe and timely manner, emergency operations, normal shutdown, and startup following a turnaround, or after an emergency shutdown;
?    Operating limits including consequences of deviation, and steps required to correct or avoid deviation;
?    Safety and health considerations including properties of, and hazards presented by, the chemicals used in the process, precautions necessary to prevent exposure, including engineering controls, administrative controls, and personal protective equipment, control measures to be taken if physical contact or airborne exposure occurs, quality control for raw materials and control of hazardous chemical inventory levels, and any special or unique hazards; and
?    Safety systems and their functions.

Operating procedures are readily accessible to employees who work in or maintain the anhydrous ammonia process.  The operating procedures shall be reviewed as often as necessary to assure that they reflect current operating practice, including changes that result from changes in process chemicals, technology, and equipment, and changes to stationary sources.  Plant management will certify annually that the operating procedures are current and accurate.  A copy of the certification form is provided in this section of the RMP.  

The Plant has developed and implemented safe work practices to provide for the control of hazards during operations such as lockout/tagout; confined space entry; opening process equipment or piping; and control over entrance into a stationary source by maintenance, contractor, laboratory, or other support personnel.  These safe work practices shall apply to employees and contractor employees.

TRAINING [40 CFR 68.71] 

Each employee that will operate the anhydrous ammonia process, will be trained in its operating procedures prior to being allowed to work on or with the system.  The training shall include emphasis on the specific safety and health hazards, emergency operations including shutdown, and safe work practices applicable to the employee's job tasks.  The plant will incorporated materials developed by the Ammonia Institute in personnel training.

The Plant will provide refresher training at least every three years, and more often if necessary, to each employee involved in operating the anhydrous ammonia process to assure that the employee understands and adheres to the current operating procedures of the process.  Records of training events will be maintained by the Training Coordinator that documents the identity of the employee, the date of training, and the means used to verify that the employee understood the training.  An example recordkeeping form is included in an attachment of this section.



MECHANICAL INTEGRITY [40 CFR 68.73] 

The Plant has established and implemented a written maintenance program covering the mechanical integrity of the anhydrous ammonia process equipment.  Maintenance personnel receive training in an overview of the ammonia process, the hazards associated with the system and relevant sections of the RMP. 

The anhydrous ammonia storage system is visually inspected once per shift by operators and by security during evening hours.  Problems identified during the visual inspection are immediately reported to the Plant Engineer. 

The Plant Engineer or designee conducts a thorough review of the anhydrous ammonia tank, equipment, piping, and safety equipment on a quarterly basis. Other mechanical tests will be performed in accordance with manufacturer recommendations.  For example, excess flow valves, pressure relief valves and other tank ancillary equipment will be thoroughly inspected every five years (last inspection 11/06).      

The Plant Engineer will maintain records of inspections and tests.  The documentation will identify the date of the inspection or test, the name of the person who performed the inspection or test, the serial number or other identifier of the equipment on which the inspection or test was performed, a description of the inspection or test performed, and the results of the inspection or test.

Equipment deficiencies that are determined to be outside acceptable limits (defined by the process safety information) will be corrected before further use or in a safe and timely manner when means are taken to assure safe operation. In the construction of new plant equipment, management will assure that the equipment is fabricated to be suitable for the process application for which it will be used.  Appropriate checks and inspections will be performed to assure that equipment is installed properly and consistent with design specifications and the manufacturer's instructions.  Spare parts and equipment will be suitable for the process application for which they will be used.

MANAGEMENT OF CHANGE [40 CFR 68.75] 

The Plant has established the following procedures to manage changes (except for replacements in kind) to the anhydrous ammonia storage and usage equipment and procedures.  These procedures assure that the following considerations are reviewed and addressed prior to any change:

?    The technical basis for the proposed change;
?    Impact of change on safety and health;
?    Modifications to operating procedures;
?    Necessary time period for the change, and,
?    Authorization requirements for the proposed change.

Employees involved in the operations or maintenance of the anhydrous ammonia process will be informed of and trained in the change prior to start-up of the process or affected part of the process.  If a change covered by this paragraph results in a change in the process safety information, such information shall be updated accordingly.  If a change covered by this paragraph results in a change in the operating procedures or practices, such procedures or practices shall be updated accordingly.  

PRE-STARTUP REVIEW [40 CFR 68.77]

The Plant will perform a pre-startup safety review for new stationary sources and for modified stationary sources when the modification is significant enough to require a change in the process safety information.  The pre-startup safety review shall confirm that prior to the introduction of regulated substances to a process:

?    Construction and equipment is in accordance with design specifications;
?    Safety, operating, maintenance, and emergency procedures are in place and are adequate;
?    For new stationary sources, a process hazard analysis has been performed and recommendations have been resolved or implemented before startup, and modified stationary sources meet the requirements contained in management of change; 
?    Training of each employee involved in operating a process has been completed.

Documentation of pre-startup review will be maintained by the Plant Engineer.

COMPLIANCE AUDITS [40 CFR 68.79] 

The RMP Rule requires that sites conduct an audit of the process to evaluate compliance with the prevention program requirements at least once every three years.  The Plant Engineer or designee knowledgeable in the process will conduct the audit.  An example form that can be used for the audit is included in the Audit Update Checklist section of this RMP. The plant will promptly determine and document an appropriate response to each of the findings of the compliance audit, and document that deficiencies have been corrected.  The Plant Engineer will maintain records of the most recent two audit reports.  

INCIDENT INVESTIGATION [40 CFR 68.81] 

The Plant will investigate each incident that resulted in, or could reasonably have resulted in a release of anhydrous ammonia.  An incident investigation shall be initiated as promptly as possible, but not later than 48 hours following the incident.  An incident investigation team shall be established and consist of at least one person knowledgeable in the process involved, including a contract employee if the incident involved work of the contractor, and other persons with appropriate knowledge and experience to thoroughly investigate and analyze the incident.


An incident report shall be prepared at the conclusion of the investigation that includes at a minimum:
?    Date of incident;
?    Date investigation began;
?    A description of the incident;
?    The factors that contributed to the incident; and,
?    Any recommendations resulting from the investigation.

The Plant will promptly address and resolve incident report findings and recommendations.  Resolutions and corrective actions shall be documented.  The report shall be reviewed with all affected personnel whose job tasks are relevant to the incident findings including contract employees.  The Plant Engineer shall retain incident investigation reports for five years.  An example form has been provided in the Incident Investigation Checklist section of this RMP.

EMPLOYEE PARTICIPATION [40 CFR 68.83]

It is the Plant?s policy to consult with employees on the conduct and development of process hazards analyses and on matters that effect and improve safety at the plant.  Employees will be provided access to process hazard analyses and to all other information included in this RMP.  Employee participation and comments are actively solicited during regular safety meetings.

HOT WORK PERMITS [40 CFR 68.85]

The Plant requires the issuance of a hot work permit for hot work operations conducted on or near the anhydrous ammonia process.  The permit documents that the fire prevention and protection requirements in 29 CFR 1910.252(a) have been implemented prior to beginning the hot work operations.  The permit indicates the date(s) authorized for hot work, who is performing the work, and the object on which hot work is to be performed.  The permit is required to be kept on file until completion of the hot work operations.  

CONTRACTORS [40 CFR 68.87]

The Plant will, when selecting a contractor, obtain and evaluate information regarding the contract owner or operator's safety performance and programs.  Prior to initiating work, contractors will be informed of the known potential fire, explosion, or toxic release hazards related to the contractor's work and the anhydrous ammonia process.  Contractor personnel will receive training on the relevant provisions of the RMP and emergency response plans.  The Dogwood Energy Facility has developed and implemented safe work practices to control the entrance, presence, and exit of the contract owner or operator and contract employees at the plant.

Contractor performance regarding safety will be periodically evaluated.  Contractors will be responsible for the following:

?    Assuring that each contract employee is trained in the work practices necessary to safely perform his/her job;
?    Assuring that each contract employee is instructed in the known potential fire, explosion, or toxic release hazards related to his/her job and the process, and the applicable provisions of the emergency action plan;
?    Documenting that each contract employee has received and understood the training required by this section;
?    Advising the plant of any unique hazards presented by the contract owner or operator's work, or of any hazards found by the contract owner or operator's work.
